example_sentence: Before cooking, she would carefully **pickle** the dried beans clean of any tiny stones or debris.

judged_meaning: The condition of being supreme in authority, rank, or power; the position of supreme or highest authority or power. figurative. Applied to any quality, phenomenon, practice, etc., enjoying a dominant or superior status.
sentence: I may here add that the House, under its Supremacy, would have been glad to give up some part of the sum demanded from the United States.
example_sentence: The new ruling affirmed the **supremacy** of federal law over state regulations.

judged_meaning: transitive. To divide into spaces or sections. Frequently with by or with. Obsolete.
sentence: The lines in each paragraph of the text were spaced out to match the measure of the line spacing in the heading.
example_sentence: The printer carefully spaced the page with leaden rules to separate columns of text.

judged_meaning: intransitive. With at.
sentence: He nagged at me to go with him and see the country, but I refused.
example_sentence: He tends to **nag at** every little detail.

judged_meaning: slang. A person, esp. a woman, infected with a venereal disease. Also: a prostitute. Cf. firedrake, n. 3d. Obsolete.
sentence: When the fire-ships were set on fire from the shore, the enemy did not perceive their direction till they struck their ships.
example_sentence: He warned the greenhorn to steer clear of that one, muttering she was nothing but a fireship.

judged_meaning: In silence; without speaking; without noise or commotion; noiselessly, quietly; without mention or notice.
sentence: ‘Aunt Ermeine,’ he said as silently as possible to her, ‘I must go home now.’
example_sentence: She read the message silently.

judged_meaning: intransitive. Of a hound: to run with the chase silently, to run mute (see mute, adj. 7). Obsolete. rare.
sentence: It was still too early in the year for the song thrush to mute its note.
example_sentence: The experienced hound would often mute, pursuing the deer without a sound.

judged_meaning: colloquial (originally and chiefly U.S.). transitive. With up. To arouse (a person) sexually; (also) to have sexual intercourse with (a person).
sentence: That sexed it up a bit for me, you know?
example_sentence: He spent the whole night trying to sex her up.

judged_meaning: transitive. To introduce or release (a type of animal) into an area or country, esp. as a new breed; (chiefly U.S.) spec. to deposit (young fish, spawn, oysters, etc.) in a river or lake to live or grow. Occasionally with out.
sentence: Some persons have planted them in the sea, and found them thrive very well there.
example_sentence: The state agency plans to **plant** thousands of trout in the river next spring.

judged_meaning: Originally (in full  great centaury,  greater centaury,  more centaury): a blue-flowered plant of the family Asteraceae (Compositae), perhaps Rhaponticoides centaurium or Leuzea rhapontica (cf. rhapontic, n. 2) (obsolete). In later use (usually with distinguishing word): any of various plants of (or formerly belonging to) the genus Centaurea (family Asteraceae (Compositae)). Cf. centaurea, n. Obsolete.
sentence: Yellow centaury, the common name for an herbaceous plant with yellow flowers which grows on cliffs.
example_sentence: He found a centaury blooming by the creek, its petals a deep blue.

judged_meaning: Imbued with or redolent of the principles or doctrine of the Christian Church; pious; conforming to or supporting the Church, esp. ostentatiously.
sentence: He'd been very churchy this summer and had gone on about how he wanted to become a minister.
example_sentence: He adopted a rather churchy tone when he started lecturing us about our casual Sunday plans.

judged_meaning: In the game of poker: To impose upon (an opponent) as to the value of one's hand of cards, by betting heavily upon it, speaking or gesticulating or otherwise acting in such a way as to make believe that it is stronger than it is, so as to induce him to  throw up  his cards and lose his stake, rather than run the risk of betting against the bluffer. (Of U.S. origin.) Hence, transferred of other wagering, political tactics, international diplomacy, etc. to bluff off: to frighten off or deter (an
sentence: The only answer is to say to her, ‘You can take your own course, but bluff me off!’
example_sentence: He successfully bluffed his opponents into folding, despite having a terrible hand.

judged_meaning: Of a feeling: arising from an apprehension or sense of the goodness or badness of an action, character, etc.
sentence: That of being moral and virtuous; as it is now used for those that are vicious and bad.
example_sentence: She felt a strong moral qualm about lying to her friend.

judged_meaning: transitive. To make higher (in various senses); to raise, elevate. Opposed to and frequently in conjunction with lower, v.
sentence: If the water level be lowered 1 ft., a flow 0·05 ft3/sec. will be highed 0·4 ft.
example_sentence: She carefully highered the delicate sculpture onto the pedestal.

judged_meaning: Physiology. Temporary inability to respond fully to nervous or sexual stimuli, esp. for a short period following a response to such a stimulus. Cf. refractory, adj. 7.
sentence: The ‘resistance’ or ‘refractoriness’ of some cases of psychosis to both psychotherapy and psychopharmacology may be a result of the latter's failure to create adequate structural change in the brain.
example_sentence: After a strong stimulus, the nerve entered a state of refractoriness, preventing it from firing again immediately.

judged_meaning: That grunts, croaks, etc.; that grumbles. Cf. quirk, v.2
sentence: There was a sort of a quirking noise in his throat, which she supposed had been a cough.
example_sentence: He responded with a barely audible **quirking** of discontent.

judged_meaning: transitive. To drill a new hole in (a thing); to drill (a hole) again. Also intransitive.
sentence: As soon as he had redrilled the whole army into a corps which would have done honour to the best soldier in the country, he was sent on leave for a fortnight.
example_sentence: We had to redrill the pilot holes because they were too small for the new screws.

judged_meaning: In various slang uses. A human leg. U.S.
sentence: It is made up of three segments, the shaft, the cross and the headpiece.
example_sentence: After that long hike, my shafts are killing me.

judged_meaning: transitive (reflexive). To perform or fulfil a duty, responsibility, etc., and thereby remove it; to relieve oneself of an obligation by fulfilling it.
sentence: The Follies, and the follies they have made themselves guilty of, shall be discharged.
example_sentence: He finally discharged himself of his financial obligations.

judged_meaning: Of or relating to mysterious or occult rites or practices. Cf. mystic, n. 3. Also in extended use.
sentence: Aristotle, that famous and mystical philosopher.
example_sentence: The tribe performed mystical rituals under the full moon.

judged_meaning: A noisy, riotous reveller; a person who indulges in wild drunken behaviour. Cf. roaring boy n. at  roaring, adj. adv.compounds . Now rare.
sentence: But that the Wench was a Roarer in liquor, they would not have come.
example_sentence: After too many pints, he became a real roarer, shouting songs and knocking over chairs.

judged_meaning: absol. To become surety or bail (for another). Obsolete.
sentence: The present report is stipulating that there be no ‘all-or-none’ attitude with regard to the human situation of any race, color, creed, religion, political philosophy or social position.
example_sentence: To free his friend from debtors' prison, the benevolent squire did **stipulate** for him.

judged_meaning: With a grand, stately, or haughty air; in grand style. Now usually depreciative: arrogantly; dogmatically; pompously.
sentence: He is the only Englishman pontifically blessed by Pope Pius.
example_sentence: He pontifically lectured the team on their mistakes, leaving no room for discussion.

judged_meaning: A female ruler; esp. a woman who exercises delegated authority, a female regent. Obsolete.
sentence: I am a poor woman that canna get a livelihood for my family in this country. I wad make a better living with you then. I was married to a Laird in this town and was obliged to come governante at a house in the burgh of Edinburgh for six years, and am not now.
example_sentence: As the king was still a child, his mother served as **governante** of the realm.

judged_meaning: In the technical use or terminology of a particular field; according to the exact meaning; properly, strictly. Also as sentence adverb.
sentence: We are, as yet, uncertain whether there is an overall solution to the problem technically; but we do know how to solve it, in the sense that we can do the job and will always be able to solve it.
example_sentence: A tomato is technically a fruit, not a vegetable.

judged_meaning: Painting. A thin coat of transparent colour laid over another colour so as to modify the tone.
sentence: The grain in the ear of a well-sown corn plant may be of fine white colour, or it may have a dull yellow tinge, but this latter is regarded as ‘going to glaze’ when the whole plant is subjected to such treatment as will bring out the white grain.
example_sentence: She applied a thin, transparent blue glaze to subtly alter the tone of the green layer beneath.

judged_meaning: Smeared, covered, saturated, or otherwise treated with pitch.
sentence: The said Warren Hastings and William Troughton have a good pitch'd piece of Ground, whereon the said Warren was born and bred, lying near the Bridge in Croydon.
example_sentence: The old wooden boat needed to be **pitched** to seal its hull.

judged_meaning: transitive. To reduce (the line of a road, railway, or canal) to levels or practicable gradients.
sentence: The road has been graded for four miles on its original line.
example_sentence: The crew needs to **grade** the road before paving.

judged_meaning: slang. (See quot. 1819.) Also North American, a grub-stake; a sum of money earned or saved; a store of provisions or sum of money necessary for survival during a certain period.
sentence: If they should come home together, then shall the first be a Lion, and they shall part stakes.
example_sentence: He saved his stake for years before opening his own restaurant.

judged_meaning: intransitive. Bricklaying. Of a brick or tile: to become curved or warped during firing. Cf. to house in at  phrasal verbs . Obsolete. rare.
sentence: The children house with the teacher at the summer camp.
example_sentence: If fired too quickly, a clay tile might **house**, making it unsuitable for construction.

judged_meaning: Of language, literature, or literary style: characterized by harmonious simplicity in the choice and arrangement of words; free from awkwardness, coarseness, or clumsiness; graceful, refined.
sentence: The English translation is of course elegant enough for its own purpose.
example_sentence: He appreciated the elegant simplicity of her prose.

judged_meaning: transitive. To deprive or dispossess (a person) of something. Obsolete.
sentence: The Follies, and the follies they have made themselves guilty of, shall be discharged.
example_sentence: The king discharged the rebel of all his titles.

judged_meaning: spec. Of a country, community, etc.: the state or condition of not requiring goods or commodities from elsewhere; financial or economic independence.
sentence: There was a feeling of self-sufficiency, as if a man could go it alone and be just as happy as with any of his acquaintances.
example_sentence: The nation prioritized **self-sufficiency** to avoid reliance on foreign imports.

judged_meaning: A bikini made of triangles of material joined by thin ties; spec. the lower half of this. Cf. string, n. 6c.
sentence: Tanga, the Maori dress or shirt of the same material as the Maori plaited skin flax skirt.
example_sentence: She chose a tiny tanga to avoid any tan lines.

judged_meaning: (with an agent-noun): That does a thing often; constant, habitual, regular.
sentence: The ‘frequent pulse’ has a slightly lowered blood pressure, and may indicate the presence of a failing left ventricle.
example_sentence: She's a **frequent visitor** to the local park.

judged_meaning: Sport. A person who participates in free-riding (free-riding, n. 2).
sentence: You should think of these potential competitors as freeriders: They are using the efforts of the national government, state governments and local authorities to build their systems.
example_sentence: The extreme terrain was perfect for the experienced freerider.

judged_meaning: Architecture. The masonry or rock which supports the lateral thrust of a bridge, arch, vault, etc.; the part of a valley side against which a dam is constructed. Cf. skew-back, n. 1a.
sentence: To successfully perform this procedure, the abutment tooth must be sound, sound root, and sufficiently supragingival.
example_sentence: The arch of the old bridge was supported by a massive stone abutment.

judged_meaning: Of, relating to, or characteristic of ritualism or ritualists.
sentence: The ritualistic tradition of the Roman Church is more easily retained by Catholic women than that of the Anglican and Calvinistic Churches.
example_sentence: Her approach to gardening was almost ritualistic, following the same steps precisely each time.

judged_meaning: Sufficiently early, in good time; (now chiefly U.S. Law) by a fixed time or deadline. rare before 17th cent.
sentence: My father being timelier informed of what had passed than any body else.
example_sentence: A **timely** payment of your bill will prevent late fees.

judged_meaning: Philosophy and Linguistics. In speech-act theory: an utterance viewed solely in terms of its intrinsic meaning or reference, without regard to the intention of the speaker or writer to perform a particular action, or to bring about a particular result by making it; a locutionary act. Cf. illocution, n., perlocution, n. 2.
sentence: The locution, though spoken, is not uttered; the illocution, though not spoken, is heard; and the perlocution, though not heard, is read.
example_sentence: Understanding the exact **locution** of the phrase is the first step before interpreting its intended force.

judged_meaning: In a plump way; with a full, rounded shape; to the point of plumpness.
sentence: His whole Body has been so full of Blood, that it has raised his Skin plumply.
example_sentence: The small pastry swelled plumply as it baked in the oven.

judged_meaning: Statistics. Unadjusted; not corrected by reference to modifying circumstances; spec. crude birth-rate, crude death-rate, the total figures before adjustment.
sentence: There is a considerable difference between the crude increase in population between 1841 and 1901 and the ‘net increase’.
example_sentence: The initial report presented only the **crude** figures, which still needed to be adjusted for demographic factors.

judged_meaning: A fishwife, esp. a French one. Obsolete.
sentence: Poissards, the name given by the Police to those Parisian women who threw stones and bottles at the guards during the Revolution, in an attempt to protect prisoners from execution.
example_sentence: The poissarde loudly haggled for her sole at the bustling Parisian market.

judged_meaning: transitive. To obtain, or seek to obtain, by pre-emption; esp. (chiefly North American) to secure (public land) in order to establish a pre-emptive title. Now historical.
sentence: To make the sale of land and the preemption of public lands as easy as possible, the land acts have provided for a system of land offices, with one in each district of the state, which should be the place of issue of all land warrants, certificates,.
example_sentence: A settler could preempt a plot of public land simply by building a cabin on it.

judged_meaning: The action or an act of hatching from an egg after incubation. Also (now chiefly): something which hatches from an egg or eggs, esp. a brood of young.
sentence: There are two doors at the rear of the hatch.
example_sentence: The farmer celebrated a successful **hatch** of chicks this spring.

judged_meaning: Hateful, disgusting, loathsome, repulsive, hideous, horrible. Rare in 17th and 18th centuries; revived in the 19th cent. as a literary word.
sentence: The old man's loathly face was now more distorted with rage than with pain.
example_sentence: The ancient tome described a creature with a truly **loathly** visage, enough to curdle the blood of any who beheld it.

judged_meaning: To deal gently with; to avoid overtasking (a limb); to ease, save, spare. Now colloquial (esp. in stable parlance) and dialect.
sentence: And favour your horse, or he may fall dead.
example_sentence: The jockey tried to favour the horse's left foreleg.

judged_meaning: As a necessary concomitant, prerequisite, or requirement; indispensably. Obsolete.
sentence: An event so violent, and so necessarily connected to this one, that it becomes a proof of a certain truth.
example_sentence: To gain audience with the Duke, one must **necessarily** possess a letter of introduction.

judged_meaning: Applied to earth holding standing water.
sentence: The Weather continued very hot and humid; the Ponds and stagnant Water full of Worms.
example_sentence: The stagnant earth held pools of rainwater for days.

judged_meaning: In a wide-set manner; with a loose or open structure. Obsolete.
sentence: As if the water rarely filled the hollows in which it was placed.
example_sentence: The old fishing net was woven so rarely, it barely held the smallest catches.

judged_meaning: A load carried by a vehicle; esp. the part of a load from which revenue is derived; passengers, cargo, etc.
sentence: The Apollo crew is on the moon and there they will make the first planet trip to be made by human pay loads.
example_sentence: The aircraft took off with its full payload of passengers and cargo.

judged_meaning: intransitive. Of two pieces of timber: to be joined together by means of coaks. Also: (of a piece of timber) to be joined on to another by means of coaks. Obsolete. rare.
sentence: The timbers should be joined, or coaked, if such is the local term, at intervals, and at least three main rafters should be in each side.
example_sentence: After careful shaping, the heavy deck timbers would **coak** perfectly into place.

judged_meaning: Sharp-featured, thin, pinched, as from illness or undernourishment; sickly looking. Cf. peaky, adj.2
sentence: The Peaked Hills on the Coast of Guinea.
example_sentence: After a week of fever, she looked quite peaked.

judged_meaning: Sport (chiefly U.S.). Designating a player who begins a particular game in the specified position or role; as starting pitcher, starting quarterback, etc. Cf. starting, n. compounds 2c.
sentence: The starting pitcher for the Brockton Club yesterday was Mr. L. J. O'Carroll of Boston.
example_sentence: The coach named him the **starting** quarterback for Sunday's game.

judged_meaning: figurative. Having a wide scope; extensive, comprehensive, all-inclusive; wholesale, indiscriminate.
sentence: This system of sweeping taxation.
example_sentence: The government announced **sweeping** reforms to the education system.

judged_meaning: transitive. spec. To apply or give (a medicine, a drug, a particular treatment, etc.); to treat a person with (something); to deliver a dose of. Cf. minister, v. 8.
sentence: The doctor who administers drugs by the drop, without a sense of responsibility for their effect.
example_sentence: The nurse will administer the medication at 3 PM.

judged_meaning: That is at the core or heart of something; of, relating to, or constituting the most important or significant part or aspect of something; chief, principal; essential. Frequently with to. Cf. centre, n.1 10c.
sentence: The central subject is the history of the world in its 100th year from the deluge.
example_sentence: Trust is central to any good relationship.

judged_meaning: A course habitually traversed by any one; sometimes figurative, esp. in phrase, out of one's beat: not in one's sphere or department.
sentence: My wife has a friend, a great old woman, who has taken it into her head to ‘go to the opera’. I am out of my beat in that department.
example_sentence: "Marketing strategy is a bit out of my beat; I focus on product development."

judged_meaning: figurative. In a theatre: a painted curtain let down to shield the stage from the view of the audience (= drop, n. 16), in front of which comedy or variety acts are performed; a curtain behind the drops which performs the same function. Also olio curtain.
sentence: I could have had something better; but being a frugal man, I am content with my own folio of boiled potatoes.
example_sentence: The painted olio rose, signaling the start of the vaudeville act.

judged_meaning: In a heartfelt manner; with full or unrestrained exercise of real feeling; sincerely, earnestly; fervently. Formerly also: with goodwill; cordially.
sentence: The great man himself heartily wished the whole business over.
example_sentence: I heartily agree with your assessment.

judged_meaning: transitive. To make into an animal; to represent as an animal, or in animal form.
sentence: If you can't animalize a human being, at least don't pretend that there is any connection between him and an alligator.
example_sentence: The political cartoon effectively **animalized** the corrupt official, depicting him as a greedy pig.

judged_meaning: Sorrow, distress, or disappointment due to some external circumstance or event. Frequently in with regret. Also: an instance of this (chiefly in plural).
sentence: But if he can bear this with patience and without regret, he shall be able to bear anything else with equanimity.
example_sentence: We noted with regret that the event had been cancelled.

judged_meaning: Mathematics. In J. J. Sylvester's usage: (of a method for expressing or solving an equation, etc.) regarding coefficients as functions or roots of other elements, rather than as independent elements in the equation or expression. Cf. exoscopic adj. at  exo-, prefix affix . Obsolete. rare.
sentence: In endoscopic embryos there is a tendency for the developing archegonia to become arranged radially around the apical region of the prothallus (toward its base), rather than radially around the middle (like an umbel).
example_sentence: An **endoscopic** mathematical analysis considers coefficients as functions or roots of other elements within the equation, rather than as independent constants.

judged_meaning: In hyperbolic use: To come near to killing. Used in the infinitive form after another verb with adverbial force =  to a great or impressive degree ; esp. in dressed (got up,etc.) to kill, dressed showily or impressively. colloquial.
sentence: I do believe that there are men whose hearts are quite capable of being killed with regard and courtesy.
example_sentence: She arrived at the party dressed to kill.

judged_meaning: Of or relating to bionics; (in later use esp.) designating a (usually mechanical or electronic) system or device designed to resemble part of a living organism, esp. one used as a prosthesis or enhancement for a human body; (of a person, etc.) having or enhanced by such a device. Cf. cybernetic, adj. 1.
sentence: Bionic Eye Goggles.
example_sentence: Her new **bionic** leg allowed her to run marathons again.

judged_meaning: Printing. To mount (copy) in the correct position on a sheet for use in making a printing plate; frequently const. in. Also, to make (a flat) thus.
sentence: It is not intended that a motor car shall be allowed to leave the testing ground until it has been thoroughly inspected and if necessary ‘striped’ in a suitable manner.
example_sentence: The prepress technician needs to strip all the page elements into place for the printing plate.

judged_meaning: Respectfully; with appropriate respect, deference, or courtesy. Now rare.
sentence: That each might respectively pay his respects to each other's house.
example_sentence: She replied respectively to her master's query, choosing her words carefully.

judged_meaning: Of an argument, proof, piece of evidence, etc.: compelling, cogent, convincing; clear, obvious.
sentence: What a delightful thing is a house full of children! It must be delightful to live and to look at and in such a little world so pregnant with little people!
example_sentence: The lawyer's closing argument was so **pregnant** that the jury reached a swift decision.

judged_meaning: Of pressure: exerted from above.
sentence: The superincumbent weight of snow.
example_sentence: The submersible was designed to endure the immense superincumbent pressure of the deep ocean.

judged_meaning: = goody, n.3
sentence: When the Goody-Goodies have finished the task.
example_sentence: He was such a goodygoody that he refused to join any pranks.

judged_meaning: Of a vehicle, esp. a motor car: of a racing type; designed for use in sport; that delivers high speed or performance; (also) characteristic of or resembling such a vehicle.
sentence: It is difficult to estimate the value of a single, sporty, new car as compared with a family car, even when the latter has been used by its owner's sons.
example_sentence: The new electric vehicle has a surprisingly sporty design.

judged_meaning: intransitive. To move, talk, strike, etc., very fast or without stopping, in a manner resembling machine-gun fire. Usually with adverbial complement.
sentence: The French artillery machina-gunned the Boche lines with great precision.
example_sentence: The witness began to machinegun through his answers, eager to get off the stand.

judged_meaning: Of a right, power, quality, etc.: claimed falsely or without justification.
sentence: The arrogated is liable for the debts contracted by the arrogator, though he may have been a minor or in minority.
example_sentence: She **arrogated** power without proper authorization.

judged_meaning: That fails in the performance of a duty or fulfilment of an obligation; (now chiefly) spec. that fails to meet financial commitments.
sentence: If he hath any debts, his creditors may attach them, and recover their money from the estate of a defaulting debtor.
example_sentence: Defaulting on your loan payments can have serious consequences for your credit rating.

judged_meaning: transitive. To consider, judge, or estimate, esp. by, or as the result of, calculation. Frequently with clause as object.
sentence: I reckoned you'd no such sense in your head as to have come there with that sort of an army.
example_sentence: I reckon it'll take about an hour to get there.

judged_meaning: In a specific or definite form or manner.
sentence: This was specifically so called in the act, as being something particularly belonging to and given to the parish.
example_sentence: She specifically requested the window seat.

judged_meaning: In a loom: a small device which travels backwards and forwards in the shuttle-box and drives the shuttle to and fro through the warp.
sentence: He was one of the best pickers of lock-pins in the country and he had seen all manner of locks.
example_sentence: The picker strikes the shuttle to propel it across the loom.

judged_meaning: transitive. Originally and chiefly Military. To put (esp. troops or supplies) on board a railway train. Now chiefly historical.
sentence: He entrained at Rennes, and then had to take another train that was going back to Paris because he had forgotten his passport.
example_sentence: The quartermaster entrained the artillery pieces before dawn.

judged_meaning: Tending to cause ague.
sentence: A fever-ridden man, an aguish man.
example_sentence: The raw, aguish wind bit through their coats, making them shiver uncontrollably.

judged_meaning: transitive and intransitive. To borrow (without any intention of returning); to scrounge. Australian slang.
sentence: There's the hummed one now!
example_sentence: Can I **hum** a couple of bucks for a coffee?

judged_meaning: To put in order, tidy up. Also in slang use (see quot. 1970).
sentence: When I get round to it, my hair will be in a bit of a state so I have to go and ‘straighten’ it, as they say on the TV.
example_sentence: We need to **straighten** out this whole mess before the boss sees it.

judged_meaning: intransitive. Of a pigeon: to set up its tail feathers. Obsolete.
sentence: They could not well rump him for his Poysoning and Perjury, as there were no Judges in Ireland.
example_sentence: The pigeon rumped, setting its tail feathers proudly erect.

judged_meaning: With adverbial accusative. to talk one's way in: to gain admission by persuasion. Similarly with out.
sentence: He must have talked to her. I can hear him. ‘Come on!’ he says to her.
example_sentence: She managed to **talk her way into** the exclusive club without an invitation.

judged_meaning: figurative. An intense and decisive contest; a dispute or competition.
sentence: In the end, the final was something of a shoot-out.
example_sentence: The final round of the debate turned into a real **shootout** between the two leading candidates.

judged_meaning: Spreading, covering; enveloping, surrounding. Also in extended use.
sentence: Mantling Broth, in Cookery, is such as boils over and gathers like a head.
example_sentence: A thick fog was slowly mantling the valley, obscuring the distant peaks.

judged_meaning: U.S. Military slang (derogatory). A member of the military, esp. a career soldier. Frequently with modifying word.
sentence: The emetic is said to be found also in all parts of North America, and is there known under the name of ‘puke’, a word which we believe has the same sound and meaning as ‘pukeweed’ or ‘puckeweed’.
example_sentence: Don't listen to him; he's just another lifer puke complaining about regulations.

judged_meaning: An urn-shaped Chinese bronze wine-vessel of the Shang to Middle Chou period (1500 249 b.c.).
sentence: His mother is attired in a green silk hat trimmed with orange flowers ; and a le'i made of orange blossoms, orange feathers and orange fruit.
example_sentence: An exquisite bronze *lei* from the Shang period graced the exhibit.

judged_meaning: Deliberately and with full awareness; in a manner characterized by reflective self-awareness.
sentence: The most extraordinary of all was a lady who walked up the town on crutches, with a little child self-consciously dangling from her arm.
example_sentence: The novelist **selfconsciously** played with genre conventions in her latest work.

judged_meaning: Finance. transitive. To acknowledge the receipt of and agree to pay (a bill of exchange or a draft). Formerly also  intransitive with of (obsolete).
sentence: The draft was accepted by Mr. Gellatley.
example_sentence: The buyer must accept the draft before the goods can be shipped.

judged_meaning: transitive. To cause (someone) to feel confused or perplexed because they cannot understand something (as a difficult question, a complex subject, etc.). Frequently in passive. Now the principal sense.
sentence: ‘What is all this to you?’ demanded the old lady—‘I can't make it out.’ ‘That's just what you are always puzzling us about,’ said Mr. Snodgrass.
example_sentence: I was puzzled by his sudden silence.

judged_meaning: That takes or receives something, in various senses. Also: inclined or tending to acquire things; acquisitive; rapacious (frequently contrasted with giving).
sentence: He had no taking heart for the business in hand.
example_sentence: He's always **taking**, never giving back to the community.

judged_meaning: slang. To arrest; to seize.
sentence: An Indian boy was snaffled to help in the kitchen.
example_sentence: Police quickly snaffled the fleeing suspect.

judged_meaning: transitive. To utter or express in a loud voice or with a roar; to shout or call (something) out. Also with direct speech as object.
sentence: Then she routed and roared.
example_sentence: The sergeant routed, "Charge!"

judged_meaning: Frequently as a count noun. In extended use: a set of opinions or ideas held by an individual or group; a theory or attitude which acts as a guiding principle for behaviour; an outlook or world view.
sentence: Philosophy of the mind is a term applied to those inquiries that consider the mental faculties in general.
example_sentence: Her philosophy is to always be kind.

However, in rare, highly ironic contexts, "merely" can be used to dramatically **understate** an extraordinary achievement, thereby highlighting its magnificence through contrast.

He didn't just win; he *merely* redefined the entire sport with his performance.

judged_meaning: Any of several small, multicoloured, live-bearing fishes of the genus Poecilia (family Poeciliidae), found in fresh and brackish waters from the southern United States to northern South America, which are popular aquarium fishes and have been bred in many colour varieties. Frequently with distinguishing word.
sentence: We shall look at them at the end of our first day, and on the morrow we will go to see the mollies.
example_sentence: We just added a new black molly to our aquarium.

judged_meaning: transferred. To make a noise as of liquid issuing from a bottle, bubbling, or the like; to utter intermittent guttural sounds.
sentence: His little rivulet, That gurgleth and gargleth around his dwelling-place.
example_sentence: The baby began to gurgle contentedly.

judged_meaning: spec. originally U.S. An organized association or gang of violent criminals; an organization engaged in large-scale criminal activity. Also (usually as the Mob): the Mafia.
sentence: We have the usual story of a small-time crook who finally becomes the head of a large mob.
example_sentence: The FBI has been trying to infiltrate the local mob for years.

judged_meaning: Of seed: To be sufficient for (a certain area).
sentence: The next thing we shall do is to sow the Fields, and sow them well, because we had rather have an abundance of Barley  than an Abundance of Wheat: and so if we find a Field sown to Wheat.
example_sentence: Does this small bag of seeds **sow** the whole garden?

judged_meaning: transitive. To warn (a person) of or against potential danger or future error. Also with subordinate clause.
sentence: He would admonish me to mind my way.
example_sentence: The coach admonished the young player, who was about to attempt a risky move that could cause injury.

judged_meaning: Without moderation, to excess; persistently; recklessly, with abandon.
sentence: The young people got up hard against the wall.
example_sentence: They partied hard all weekend.

judged_meaning: The action of mocking or teasing a person; joking, railing, bantering; (also) an instance of this. Now rare and archaic.
sentence: I tried hard to get some quizzings from him about the war, but he had seen so much, he was never at a loss for words.
example_sentence: The playful quizzing about his terrible singing always made him blush, but he secretly enjoyed the attention.

judged_meaning: A cut of jewel in the shape of a pointed oval; a jewel cut in such a shape. Frequently attributive. Cf. marquise, n. 4b.
sentence: The seeds are employed in oil and cake, both of which articles possess a very high value. The seed contains about 44 per cent. of oil, which is called Navette or Olive Oil.
example_sentence: Her new ring sparkled with a striking **navette** diamond.

judged_meaning: That shakes the earth; that causes earthquakes.
sentence: He was an earth-shaking, fire-railing, thunder-claiming, and hail-storm-whirling prophet.
example_sentence: The earthshaking tremors sent dust flying from the old stone walls.

judged_meaning: In an unusual manner; esp. in a pleasingly unusual or old-fashioned manner.
sentence: This charming gentleman, so quaintly and happily eccentric in his costume, was no other than Lord Glenallan.
example_sentence: The old cottage was quaintly furnished.

judged_meaning: In detail. Obsolete.
sentence: Then he broke into a little song, and rattled his sticks together, and fell sundry.
example_sentence: The chronicler recorded the events sundry.

judged_meaning: = sap-green, n. Obsolete.
sentence: As I have known thee sapp the Whips of every one of these Scented Villains.
example_sentence: She tinted the fabric with a pale sap.

judged_meaning: A piece of work; esp. a small and discrete piece of work done as part of one's regular occupation or profession.
sentence: I shall not, in the mean time, neglect to send you the job of the four leaves.
example_sentence: I just finished that last editing **job** for the client.

judged_meaning: In a roving manner; with an inclination towards roving.
sentence: I have got two Children by this Woman, whom I leave to my Wife and Family; but I think he may possibly have some in his Eye who look rovingly upon them.
example_sentence: He lived **rovingly**, never settling in one town for very long.

judged_meaning: Jocularly used for: A leg. Chiefly in to stir one's stumps, to walk or dance briskly,  to do one's duty zealously.
sentence: The two men were smoking stumps and drinking beer.
example_sentence: Come on, stir your stumps, or we'll miss the train!

judged_meaning: That has been racked (in various senses); esp. tortured on the rack; tormented; strained to or beyond the limit.
sentence: And still as on a racked cross I stand, Thou art thyself my constant tormenter.
example_sentence: He was racked with pain after the fall.

judged_meaning: Mechanics. A projection or tooth acting as a detent, e.g. in a lock or clutch mechanism; a catch which engages the teeth of a ratchet wheel; = pawl, n.1 1b.
sentence: If one of these is removed from its place, the whole dog will roll.
example_sentence: The *dog* engaged the ratchet, holding the load securely.

judged_meaning: transitive. To carry, bear, or convey; to bring.
sentence: A small boy porting a big basket on his shoulder.
example_sentence: Please **port** the updated data to the new server by the end of the day.

judged_meaning: A large or substantial amount. colloquial.
sentence: Chuck, a strong, sturdy pony.
example_sentence: I'll need a good **chunk** of time to get that report finished.

judged_meaning: An aggressive, ruthless, or tenacious person, esp. a lawyer or government official.
sentence: The junkyard dogs of the Treasury would try to block even such moderate proposals.
example_sentence: As a prosecutor, she was a junkyarddog on cross-examination, never letting a witness off easy.

judged_meaning: intransitive. Of the sea, an expanse of water, etc.: to have or present a ruffled or crinkled surface (in earlier use somewhat threatening); to be covered with small waves; (also) to form ripples.
sentence: When a full Flood swells the Stream below, The Shagreen of the smooth Sea to show. The Sea, tho' smooth, the ipples yet may show.
example_sentence: The lake rippled in the gentle breeze.

judged_meaning: transitive. With with. To entrust (a person, etc.) with the care of or responsibility for a task, a valuable object, etc.
sentence: Trust with a man's life a thing more precious than life and the man would go to his grave, but if he took one step in wrongness and the man lived you'd hang him.
example_sentence: I trust her with the keys to the office.

judged_meaning: = dialectic, n.1 1a. Now rare.
sentence: The Dialect of the Church is a very different one from that of the Court.
example_sentence: Through careful **dialect**, they hoped to reconcile the conflicting theories.

judged_meaning: Designating a unit of measurement in a system based on the force between two magnetic poles, or (equivalently) between two current-carrying wires, and an arbitrary assignment of value to the permeability of free space. Contrasted with electrostatic, adj. 2.
sentence: The electro-magnetic system is an arbitrary system in which a current of 1 ampere in each of two parallel wires at a separation of 1 metre, divided by 10−7 m, will produce a force of 1 newton between them at their poles.
example_sentence: In some older systems, **electromagnetic** units for current and voltage were derived from magnetic force, unlike electrostatic units based on charge.

judged_meaning: A sheep which becomes attached to a particular spot or object. Also placer sheep.
sentence: I'm a abler. I'm a black marketeer. I make my living on the black market.
example_sentence: That old ewe is a placer, stubbornly attached to her favorite patch of clover.

judged_meaning: transitive. To assign or award (an office or dignity); to grant (a favour, etc.); to hand over (power, etc.). Usually with to.
sentence: I had not the power of acceding any favour whatever on account of the mere performance of a religious service.
example_sentence: The council acceded the special permit to the developers.

judged_meaning: transitive. To make mad; to drive out of one's mind; to excite to frenzy or uncontrollable anger. Also, in weakened sense: to irritate, annoy, vex.
sentence: To have had the face to say so, and without any blush—without any fear that his wife would hear him, or madden for it in her own mind, is a matter, Mr. Thornton said, he did not know what to make of.
example_sentence: The endless delays madden me.

judged_meaning: intransitive. To make a repost or return thrust. Frequently in figurative context. Cf. riposte, v. 1.
sentence: I have been taught that there is nothing more ridiculous in the world than a woman who refuses to repost, who passes up an opportunity to ‘answer back’.
example_sentence: After the senator's cutting remark, her opponent quickly **reposted** with a witty, incisive comeback.

judged_meaning: According to ordinary procedure or custom; as a matter of course. Cf. course, n. 20.
sentence: You know what a big deal I've got to make in life as soon as I am able to make it—big acourse of things!
example_sentence: They followed the old customs acourse, never questioning the traditions.

judged_meaning: transitive. U.S. To render (a question, matter, etc.) irrelevant or of no practical significance.
sentence: He was the first man who had mouted the possibility of a national army, but he never got beyond discussing how one could be organised.
example_sentence: The out-of-court settlement effectively **mooted** the need for a lengthy trial.

judged_meaning: transitive. To prosecute (a person or  suit) at law. Now regional and humorous.
sentence: The poor Irish were persecuted with the most merciless cruelty.
example_sentence: My old neighbor used to threaten he'd persecute me for every stray leaf that landed in his yard.

judged_meaning: To be deprived of (something) in a contest or game; to forfeit (a stake); hence, to be defeated in (a game, battle, lawsuit); to fail to carry (a motion). Also in Cricket: To have (a wicket) taken by an opponent. Const. to.
sentence: A little before nightfall we came within shot of their line, when our scout fell into an ambush of the enemy, who lost only one man.
example_sentence: We might lose the match if we don't score soon.

judged_meaning: transitive. slang. To strike or shoot (a person). Obsolete.
sentence: There is something so awful in the way some people ‘plump’ out a sentence that I am sometimes tempted to believe they would never have said it had it come out naturally.
example_sentence: He vowed to plump the scoundrel if he didn't leave.

judged_meaning: Of an egg: left soft in cooking, lightly cooked.
sentence: It is a rare occurrence to find him in the saddle.
example_sentence: I like my eggs rare.

judged_meaning: U.S. regional. A menacing supernatural creature; a goblin, bogey, or ghost.
sentence: I'm not in favor of this boogor business.
example_sentence: "Don't go near that old well after dark, or the booger might get you!"

judged_meaning: Of a musical instrument, esp. a wind instrument: having no keys; played by means other than keys. Cf. key, n.1 19.
sentence: These keyless doors open to every stranger.
example_sentence: The recorder is a keyless wind instrument, played by covering finger holes.

judged_meaning: To transport in a vehicle or craft operating a shuttle service. Also transferred.
sentence: There is a new shutting of passengers and goods between London and Birmingham.
example_sentence: The hotel regularly **shuttles** guests to and from the airport.

judged_meaning: Haughty, self-inflated. Obsolete. rare.
sentence: The dry sublimed residue is first dried at a temperature of about 60°C. in a vacuum.
example_sentence: The old baron, ever sublimed, viewed common folk as mere dust beneath his notice.

judged_meaning: The action or an act of placing a person in custody or detention, esp. as a punishment or while awaiting trial; commitment to a place of incarceration, correction, etc.; imprisonment, detention. Cf. commitment, n. 1a(a).
sentence: A young Gentleman was committed to Newgate in Committal for some Crime.
example_sentence: The judge's order for his **committal** to detention was issued after the bail hearing.

judged_meaning: Of money, valuables, etc.: deposited in a bank.
sentence: A little banked-up snow was still there.
example_sentence: She banked her bonus as soon as it arrived.

judged_meaning: transitive. To cause or require (a person) to recant a heresy, etc.; to sentence to recantation. Now rare and historical.
sentence: If he will abjure from his errors, and submit to the faith.
example_sentence: The ecclesiastical court hoped to abjure the accused heretic.

judged_meaning: intransitive. Of a seed or growing thing: to take root and grow to become a plant. Obsolete.
sentence: Some persons have planted them in the sea, and found them thrive very well there.
example_sentence: When the ground softened with rain, the forgotten seeds began to **plant** and show their first green shoots.

judged_meaning: Of, relating to, or characteristic of George Eliot or her writing or thought; resembling or influenced by Eliot's work; rare before second half of 20th cent.
sentence: In 1910, though, he began writing a series of very long poems, first The Four Quartets and then The Waste Land, the whole Eliotic movement being centered around these works, and all derived from them.
example_sentence: Her new novel possesses an eliotic depth, exploring complex moral dilemmas with nuanced psychological insight.

judged_meaning: A photographic image produced by placing an object on a photographic film and exposing both to a magnetic field. Obsolete. rare.
sentence: We have tried to get from the various magnetographs the true total variation at different times.
example_sentence: The obsolete **magnetograph** showed a faint impression of the metal object, formed on the film by an applied magnetic field.

judged_meaning: A small strong cotton fishing line connecting the main line to the hook. Cf. snell, n.
sentence: If you want to give the hook a good pull the line in front of it is tied with some fine line, and this ganging line is thrown clear of the hook.
example_sentence: He tied the hook directly to the strong cotton ganging that connected to his main line.

judged_meaning: That provides refreshment or recreation; reinvigorating.
sentence: A re-creating genius that creates all things from nothing and, indeed, as a great artist has said, makes all things new.
example_sentence: After a long hike, the cool mountain stream felt wonderfully recreating.

judged_meaning: A sound, often repetitive or sustained, resembling that of drumming.
sentence: She was in the kitchen and could hear the old-fashioned drums and horns.
example_sentence: The drum of the rain on the roof was strangely comforting.

judged_meaning: Reduction or loss of vision in dim light; night blindness.
sentence: In the latter years, after having been long deprived of sight, they become liable to what is called nyctalopia, that is a kind of dimness in their eyes.
example_sentence: He suspected nyctalopia after struggling to see clearly when driving at dusk.

judged_meaning: Originally Scottish. transitive. To place or set down heavily or suddenly. Frequently with down. Also reflexive: = sense 2a. Cf. plump, v.1 2.
sentence: I sat myself down to a hearty meal, and he did the same; and there we plunked on opposite sides of the fire.
example_sentence: He plunked his heavy backpack down on the floor with a sigh.

judged_meaning: transitive. Biology and Physiology. To release or make available (a substance, cells, etc.).
sentence: The enormous excess of money at large is mobilized into a little capital.
example_sentence: Hormones can mobilize stored glucose from the liver when energy is needed.

judged_meaning: To perfect finally or in detail; to put the final and completing touches to (a thing). Also with off, up.
sentence: Our Ship being in a little Bay, we finished the same Day.
example_sentence: She spent the afternoon **finishing off** the final details on the sculpture.

judged_meaning: transitive. To thrust (a weapon) into.
sentence: Stubbing out a cigarette on the edge of the table he gave himself a little shake.
example_sentence: He stubbed the knife into the wooden door.

judged_meaning: More fully pug-engine. A small locomotive used chiefly for shunting; a contractor's engine.
sentence: There was an old pug-engine which would go into one of the hills and haul coal to the top of it.
example_sentence: The old pug tirelessly shunted coal wagons in the sidings.

judged_meaning: At any rate, in any case; nevertheless: = anyhow, adv. 3a, 3c.
sentence: They have got to fight for their country and they are all doing it anyhow.
example_sentence: I'm not sure why it happened, but **anyhows**, we'll figure it out.

judged_meaning: The action of sending something by mail; posting.
sentence: The cost of the mailing was fully paid for by a grant from the National Council for the Arts.
example_sentence: The mailing of the package was delayed by the holiday.

judged_meaning: figurative. Greatly, colossally (cf. pyramidal, adj. 2b). Obsolete. rare.
sentence: He was buried, not pyramidally, but with a flat headstone, like a plain soldier.
example_sentence: The philosopher's intellect was **pyramidally** profound, grasping concepts far beyond his peers.

judged_meaning: colloquial (originally U.S.). Short for gin rummy n. at  compounds 2.
sentence: After the second gin, which he had drunk slowly, the young man had grown quite confidential.
example_sentence: We played gin until midnight.

judged_meaning: Lively, brisk, in high spirits; lusty, sprightly, merry; aggressively high-spirited, disposed to exult or triumph,  cocky . Now dialect and in U.S.
sentence: The boat was very narrow, and so inclined that she was ‘crank by the ground’.
example_sentence: He was feeling **mighty crank** and ready to challenge anyone.

judged_meaning: Australian slang. A horse, esp. a racehorse.
sentence: The neddy took off before I'd cleared the fence.
example_sentence: Our neddy won the last race.

judged_meaning: Amber which contains an insect, leaf, or other piece of organic matter embedded and preserved within it. Occasionally also: any organism or organic matter embedded and preserved in amber. Chiefly in plural. Now rare.

example_sentence: He carefully examined the **inclusum**, a fly perfectly preserved within a polished piece of ancient amber.

judged_meaning: With a nonchalant, detached, or superior air; dismissively; casually, blithely.
sentence: A gentleman, who looked at us very airily, and said ‘Good-day’.
example_sentence: "We'll just figure it out," she said airily, dismissing their detailed plans with a wave of her hand.

judged_meaning: Chiefly in predicative use. Of a door, gate, or window: slightly or partially open. Also in extended use.

example_sentence: The kitchen window was left ajar overnight.

judged_meaning: Association Football. A long pass upfield towards the forwards; a style of play characterized by this. Cf. route one, n.

judged_meaning: With regard to the emotions.

example_sentence: She felt **emotionally** drained after the difficult conversation.

judged_meaning: In extended use, applied to similar vessels used elsewhere. A small rowing boat or (later also) a similar vessel propelled by other means, frequently an outboard motor; esp. (a) a small boat carried on board, or towed behind, a larger vessel (such as a man-of-war, merchant ship, or yacht) for use as a lifeboat or tender; (b) a small open boat with one pair of oars, used for leisure or recreation.
sentence: The dinghy of a frigate consists of one deck covered by a canvas cover, and with a tent which may be extended at pleasure over it.
example_sentence: We took the dinghy ashore from the yacht.

judged_meaning: To make foul or dirty, esp. on the surface; to begrime, stain, tarnish. Also spec., of a child or patient: to make foul by defecation (esp. when involuntary); frequently absol.
sentence: A black spot upon the cloth is supposed to have been soiled with a drop of blood.
example_sentence: Please be careful not to soil your clean uniform before the ceremony.

judged_meaning: transitive. To make or set free (from, of); to invest with a franchise or privilege; = enfranchise, v. Now rare.
sentence: The government will be asked to grant the right to set up a bank to ‘franchise’ credit for the car trade.
example_sentence: The new legislation aimed to **franchise** a broader segment of the population.

judged_meaning: Unduly forward in offering one's services, or in taking business upon oneself; doing, or prone to do, more than is asked or required; interfering, intrusive. In later use esp.: inclined to assert authority in a self-important or pompous way, esp. with regard to petty or trivial matters. (Now the usual sense.)
sentence: I have been too officious in my correspondence with him.
example_sentence: The officious clerk lectured us on the correct way to fill out the form, even though it seemed perfectly clear.

judged_meaning: To pluck out (hair) by the roots. Also absol.
sentence: These plants should be grubbed up and moved every spring.
example_sentence: She carefully grubbed out the stubborn ingrown hair.

judged_meaning: transitive. To grade or resurface (a road); to provide with a crown (crown, n. 26c). Occasionally intransitive or with up. Now rare.
sentence: The highway was in excellent condition, being fairly well ‘piked’, as the country folk put it.
example_sentence: The road crew worked to pike the dirt track, ensuring water would run off.

judged_meaning: One in whom the quality is personified; a diligent person.
sentence: The Diligence, which was to have taken me to Paris in three days, could not go.
example_sentence: When it comes to precise work, she is **diligence** itself.

judged_meaning: Having the property of being traduced or transmitted; passing on to another; hereditary; traditional; derivative. Cf. traduction, n. 3b. Obsolete.
sentence: What was called by him (though by a word not in general use) the traductive and the imitative faculty.
example_sentence: The **traductive** nature of the ancestral ailment was a source of great concern.

judged_meaning: Alchemy. = bufo, n. Obsolete.
sentence: They are not to be blamed for having been toads. They are not to blame if parents do not understand.
example_sentence: The old alchemical grimoires often referenced the toad as a potent ingredient.

judged_meaning: Chemistry. Forming names of compounds and salts of iron in which the element has a higher oxidation state or valency, esp. +3. Hence: designating this oxidation state, or iron in this state. Contrasted with ferrous, adj. 2.
sentence: Ferric oxide.
example_sentence: Rust is primarily composed of various ferric oxides.

judged_meaning: With reference to consumption: richly, fully; with large quantities or generous portions; amply, copiously. Cf. generous, adj. 6b.
sentence: His Grace having taken a plentiful and generous Supper of Fowl.
example_sentence: Spread the butter generously on the warm toast.

judged_meaning: = greyhound racing, n.
sentence: Gracing has long been an all-embracing term for greyhound racing.
example_sentence: We're off to the gracing tonight to see the dogs run.

judged_meaning: (Chiefly in scientific use.) = mammalian, adj. Obsolete.
sentence: In quadrupeds and mamigerous birds the ova are white; while in others they are coloured.
example_sentence: The paleontologist identified a new **mammiferous** species from the Eocene epoch.

judged_meaning: Dentistry. A tooth that anchors or supports a prosthesis. Also abutment tooth.
sentence: To successfully perform this procedure, the abutment tooth must be sound, sound root, and sufficiently supragingival.
example_sentence: The dentist prepared the molar, using it as the **abutment** for the new bridge.

judged_meaning: gen. Characterized by or exhibiting repetition; that repeats or is repeated.
sentence: He was a repeating, but not an extensive writer.
example_sentence: The repeating alarm clock finally woke me up.

judged_meaning: Having eyes of gold, a golden colour, or that shine like gold. Also figurative.
sentence: Golden-eyed Shiner.
example_sentence: Her **goldeneyed** stare unnerved him.

judged_meaning: Metal ore of a brittle, crumbly nature. With distinguishing word indicating the type of metal. Cf. slick, n.2
sentence: The old man had seen it done a dozen times before, though not always so easily or with such good effect. As he stood, wondering what was in store, the ram went into action.
example_sentence: The **iron ram** crumbled readily under the pickaxe.

judged_meaning: transitive. To indulge, enliven, or gratify (a feeling or personal quality). Obsolete.
sentence: They were often used as a recreation or a solace.
example_sentence: The cheerful music recreated her flagging spirits.

judged_meaning: With defining words, applied to various plants whose leaves, flowers, etc. are used in the same way as tea, either for beverages, or medicinally (also to the leaves, etc. themselves, or the drink infused from them). (See also tea-plant, n., tea-tree, n.)
sentence: This is the herb that is also known as chamomile or Roman tea.
example_sentence: Many people enjoy peppermint tea for both its refreshing taste and digestive benefits.

judged_meaning: transitive. To remove (dirt, impurities, etc.) by rinsing. Usually with away, from, off, out. Also in extended use.
sentence: A few of us had to be rinsed out of the city, out to the country and to the water.
example_sentence: Please rinse the soap off your hands thoroughly.

judged_meaning: Designating a right, interest, quality, etc., considered to be such according to personal judgement, without reference to the opinions of others.
sentence: A self-judged man never thinks himself equal to any other man's idea of him, unless his own idea is that he is better than all men.
example_sentence: She upheld her **selfjudged** values, regardless of what others thought.

judged_meaning: That has become or been made disjointed or disconnected; (of a body part, etc.) dislocated, out of joint. Also figurative. Cf. unjoint, v.

example_sentence: After the fall, the doll's arm hung unjointed.

judged_meaning: A young pike (fish), Esox lucius.
sentence: A pilotless airship will be fitted with four separate flight pods: pilots; navigator; computer ; and propulsion.
example_sentence: We spotted a pod lurking in the reeds, its sharp little teeth already visible.

judged_meaning: To keep watch over, keep in charge, herd,  keep  (sheep, etc.); to rule (men). Only in Old English and early Middle English Obsolete.
sentence: If any ship should hold one hundred and eighty tons.
example_sentence: It was the boy's duty to **hold** the sheep on the high pasture.

judged_meaning: transitive. To utter (something) with suppressed laughter. Usually with direct speech as object.
sentence: Titter, to sway; totter; as ‘He tittered up to the door.’
example_sentence: She tittered, "I can't believe he actually said that!"

judged_meaning: = football, n. 2b.
sentence: I found a -footer.
example_sentence: The footer's on TV at three o'clock.

judged_meaning: In a radiant manner; brightly, splendidly.
sentence: The same principle may be radiantly extended to the other parts of the solar system.
example_sentence: She smiled **radiantly** as she accepted the award.

judged_meaning: Quickly, immediately. Obsolete.
sentence: The author's ripely considered opinion that the moderns cannot produce art of ‘high aesthetic quality’.
example_sentence: "Tell me ripely what transpired!"

judged_meaning: colloquial. Exceedingly well; excellently; extremely.
sentence: The Duke was primely pleased with what he saw of his daughter-in-law.
example_sentence: Everything's going primely with the new project.

judged_meaning: spec. (= earthquake shock n.). A sudden and more or less violent shake of a part of the earth's surface; a single movement of the series of movements constituting an earthquake.
sentence: The Shock is like a Cataract in the Air.
example_sentence: A sudden shock made the building tremble.

judged_meaning: Firm in structure but yielding to pressure; brittle; crisp. Also: friable, crumbly. Obsolete.
sentence: Crimp, in gardening and husbandry, that kind of dry mould, which, when dug up with a spade or other tool, breaks into small pieces.
example_sentence: The old biscuit was so crimp it crumbled at the slightest touch.

judged_meaning: In extended use in the fields of sociology, anthropology, psychology, philosophy, etc. Frequently with reference to the development and structure of village and city communities (opposed to heterogenetic).
sentence: It can only be in the same way that all the ‘suburban’ and ‘urban’ units were originally ‘orthogenetic’.
example_sentence: The city's orthogenetic development maintained its distinct character, evolving largely from its own internal traditions rather than external influences.

judged_meaning: transitive. To restore (muscles, nerves, etc.) to (some degree of) normal function, esp. after injury; to redevelop (movement or other function).
sentence: Many patients continue to re-educate their muscles.
example_sentence: I'm doing exercises to reeducate my shoulder after surgery.

judged_meaning: The action or faculty of perceiving or noting a distinction between things; discrimination, differentiation; an instance of this. Chiefly with between, of.
sentence: What in the mind of man is discernment is in God absolute truth.
example_sentence: A good leader needs strong **discernment** to distinguish true solutions from superficial fixes.

judged_meaning: In wire-drawing: a revolving frame or drum round which the wire is wound as part of the drawing process.
sentence: When the wire has been drawn through the block, it is passed around a large reel and then passed through another block.
example_sentence: The reel takes up the wire as it's drawn through the die.

judged_meaning: colloquial. Sport (originally and chiefly Golf). A long, accurate, and usually powerful shot or ball. Cf. raking, adj.1 2.
sentence: He had a fire burning in the room, with a raker on it.
example_sentence: His approach shot was a perfect raker, landing just feet from the pin.
